00:04:18.727 --> 00:04:20.560
SAROO BRIERLEY: Yeah,
that was really quick,

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:24.610
but it's a 10-hour story that's
been compressed into two hours.

00:04:24.610 --> 00:04:27.220
And now it's probably even more.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:30.610
But I lived in the
slum suburb of India.

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:32.080
This is 29 years ago.

00:04:32.080 --> 00:04:33.970
And I was only about
five years of age

00:04:33.970 --> 00:04:36.370
and stood over about
a meter in height.

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:40.040
And one night, I went with
my brother from my hometown

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:43.510
and caught a train to
our local neighboring

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:46.960
station, which was a couple
of hours, just down the road.

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:54.115
And so we got there
about 9, 8 o'clock--

00:04:54.115 --> 00:04:57.220
sorry, 8 or 9 o'clock.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:00.460
And I was quite tired
and weary and sleepy.

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:02.990
I'm only five years of age.

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:04.880
And it's past my bedtime.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:07.300
And so I grabbed
my brother's hand.

00:05:07.300 --> 00:05:10.430
And we stepped off the train
and onto the station platform

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:12.880
and I saw a chair
in front of me.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:15.880
And so I pulled my
brother towards it.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.730
And my feet are doing the
talking, as they sort of do it

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:19.950
when you're tired.

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:21.280
And I sat down.

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:23.170
And my brother said,
stay here for a minute.

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:25.300
I'll come back to get you.

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:27.836
I went to sleep.

00:05:27.836 --> 00:05:29.710
And when I wake up, not
knowing whether I was

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.200
sleep for two hours,
three hours, or more--

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:36.700
but when I woke up, my brother
was nowhere to be seen.

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:41.380
And so I thought, he's on
the train that is standing.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:43.060
Whether it's the
same one that I came

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:46.930
from my hometown or a different
one, I wasn't sure of.

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:51.130
But I made that
impulse decision--

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:55.430
groggy impulse decision-- to
board the train thinking he's

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:55.930
on there.

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:58.840
So I boarded it, went
to sleep in a cubicle,

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:03.160
not knowing that I'm
going on a train that

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:04.900
has a destination unknown.

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:11.260
So I ended up 32 hours, 1,600
kilometers from the safe zone

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:15.010
to a place called Kolkata, where
I survived for months, going

00:06:15.010 --> 00:06:20.620
through trials and tribulations
of some of the things of come

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:25.040
across people that said that
they'd help me try and find

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.566
my hometown, but they
had an ulterior motive,

00:06:27.566 --> 00:06:28.940
and then running
away from there,

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:32.540
and then almost drowning
in the Hooghly River twice,

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:36.610
then to coming across
boy gangs, and then going

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:40.240
to a local prison, to a juvenile
prison, to adoption home.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:43.930
And then from there being
adopted out to Australia,

00:06:43.930 --> 00:06:47.530
Tasmania, where I
always looked after,

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:53.020
loved, shown the Australian way
of life the culture, and so on.

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:57.970
But always had that nostalgia
of being reminiscing of my past

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:01.870
and what an oddity it has
been for such a long time

00:07:01.870 --> 00:07:04.900
that I couldn't conceive
how a child could

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:08.980
get from being with his
family to getting on a train

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:10.267
and getting lost.

00:07:10.267 --> 00:07:11.350
It just didn't make sense.

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:14.800
Even though it was
saddening, I had

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:20.440
to find the closure of at
least giving a valiant attempt

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.920
in trying to find my family,
whichever ways in the means

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:25.640
that I've got at hand.

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:29.740
And so in my latter 20s,
I found Google Earth.

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:36.730
And I had that option of
looking on an atlas of trying

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:40.630
to find Burhanpur, which is
the only name that I remembered

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:42.650
in the way that articulated.

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:45.430
But I had a really
good visual memory.

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:49.490
And I thought, you know, if
there's such an application

00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:54.460
that I could use on the
internet that I could match

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:58.060
what's in my memories-- of the
landmarks and the architecture

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.750
of my hometown--

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:04.970
to what I can see on cyberspace,
Google Earth, then it

00:08:04.970 --> 00:08:07.220
would make the process so
much quicker, as opposed

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:12.170
to going back to India and
trying to find Burhanpur

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:16.500
and a train station that maybe
looks the same, maybe not.

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:19.070
So I went onto Google Earth.

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:21.170
And for years and
years, I searched,

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:25.190
from going haphazardly to
becoming quite methodical

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:27.290
and strategic in the
ways that I thought

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:30.860
about looking for my hometown.

00:08:30.860 --> 00:08:35.539
And in 2011, I found that
needle in a haystack.

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:40.549
And in 2012, I found my
hometown, as well as my family

00:08:40.549 --> 00:08:42.690
as well.

00:08:42.690 --> 00:08:48.110
So that was a quick version.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.642
Even though we could
have 20 coffees and I'd

00:08:50.642 --> 00:08:52.100
tell you the 10-hour
version, which

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:56.940
I'm happy to do so, because
I don't mind it myself.

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:02.230
But yeah, it pretty
much happened like that.

00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:08.030
But I listened to myself,
my dreams, my gut feelings,

00:09:08.030 --> 00:09:10.430
and my memories as well.

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:14.660
And the hope and determination--

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.060
I was harnessed with that.

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:19.310
So I think that
those points were

00:09:19.310 --> 00:09:21.770
quite integral to
finding what I've been

00:09:21.770 --> 00:09:23.429
longing for such a long time.

00:09:23.429 --> 00:09:25.220
CASEY WHITELAW: It's
such an amazing story.

00:09:25.220 --> 00:09:27.790
Even your compressed
version like this

00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:30.500
is just so inspirational.

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:32.930
The movie has been a
huge success worldwide.

00:09:32.930 --> 00:09:34.600
What do you think about it?

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:36.350
What do you think there
is about it that's

00:09:36.350 --> 00:09:40.057
been so universally acclaimed?

00:09:40.057 --> 00:09:42.390
SAROO BRIERLEY: There's so
many attributes to the movie.

00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:44.900
And people see it in
so many different ways.

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:48.980
It resonates in people in
so many different ways.

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:56.060
I guess political to
scientific to a movement

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:59.810
in the community in
regards to adoption,

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:05.840
from having IVF to having
that option of adopting

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:10.430
as well for couples that
want to have children.

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:15.350
So that is some of the
things, but people just

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:19.320
see it in different ways,
from hope and determination.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:28.430
And I guess that's mainly the
things that I get talked about,

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:29.420
is adoption.

00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:33.350
But other people see it
in other ways, as well.

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:37.494
Do you think nurture or
nature kind of thing,

00:10:37.494 --> 00:10:39.410
in regards to when we're
bringing up children.

00:10:45.345 --> 00:10:46.850
I guess there's so many things.

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:47.810
Where do you start?

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:49.310
CASEY WHITELAW: I
wasn't joking when

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:50.450
I was saying that
